✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: Nice one

❌ Rejected the contribution.
Comment: Too hard for clash of code, too easy for a puzzle
Not too hard but i personally think that clash of code questions should be easily solvable for everyone, i really think that you should apply the  a != 0 rule as mentioned by StepBack13 below.
In my opinion a little bit too complexe for a simple clash of code. Either reduce the complexity (as mentioned below), or shift this into easy puzzles.

I tried solving this now and it took over 10 minutes.
I think it would be a better clash of code if you kept it to being parabolae that had a != 0.

Having a = 0 possible just makes the number of conditionals too complex. Each one is not too much more work, but the infinite solutions one for example is not obvious.
Was fun once solved, but not solvable in 5 minutes by most clashers I'd say.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: it is a conics section question, easily solvable.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: this contribution is cool and i think it's a good exercice just maybe change the output for being more clearer

The solution is very interesting in terms of code golfing!
I learned to use exit() instead of a else.
I am far from being a pro, but you can remove the space between the "-1" and the "if" line 6.

That said, the problem is fun. Maybe you can precise that when there is only one solution, you should still double the output, instead of discovering it in Test 5 if we do not pay attention to the output.

But it is strange to see parenthesis in the output. If I needed such program, I would ask it to output each intersection point on its own line, and with X and Y only separated by space (better for parsing). Even your input in separated by space, without parenthesis.
